      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen discussing numbers in the previous text, we used cultures from Mesoamerica (*Abya Yala*) to examine the relationship between them (<htcite0>). However, we mentioned that, generally, in textbooks, numbers are presented in a way that differs from that of a sacred mountain. Before reaching a more abstract version, let us take an intermediate step. Observe the Shona kitchen (**Figure 1**) (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "010490cd-6da9-4992-a765-8a03188da892",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Reality",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1c6f4dce-a58a-4c06-b4a8-6f509575f42a",
                     "text": "Muratu, Brian Z.",
                     "page": "pp. 56",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/UniversityJohannesburg/ShonaJohannnesburg.jpg\" id=\"imgShona\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgShona', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Photos of a Shona kitchen. In the top left, we see a photo of the kitchen with the door closed. In the top right, we see the back of the kitchen. In the bottom section, there are images of the interior of the structure. These photos were taken by Brian Z. Muratu (<htcite0>) and are being used under the terms defined by the University of Johannesburg, which shared the dissertation under the <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</a> license.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1c6f4dce-a58a-4c06-b4a8-6f509575f42a",
                     "text": "Muratu, Brian Z.",
                     "page": "pp. 56",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: What if it were in the kitchen?</b><br /><br />How would you organize numbers in a Shona kitchen?<br /><br />Notice that the Shona kitchen has a circular shape. Do you think circles would aid in this understanding?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_cooking",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Understanding the Shona Kitchen\n\nObserve the diagram presented in the work of Doctor Zvakanyorwa Wilbert Sadomba (<htcite0>) on the Shona kitchen (**Figura 2**):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cc162709-bdc3-469b-a208-e900f4570842",
                     "text": "Sadomba, Zvakanyorwa Wilbert",
                     "page": "pp. 244 - 248",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/Sadomba/ShonaHut.png\" id=\"imgShona1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgShona1', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 2</b>: Diagram of the Shona kitchen. Photograph used with permission from Doctor Zvakanyorwa Wilbert Sadomba.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Observing **Figure 2**, we see that within the circle mapping the kitchen, there are regions that delimit certain spaces; for example, the central part, which has different levels and is where cooking takes place, represented by a smaller circle (<htcite0>).\n\nAround this fire region, there are other internal regions dedicated to exclusive functions, which we will not detail here as they fall outside our main focus (<htcite1>). Now observe the figure we adapted in the previous text (**Figure 3**):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cc162709-bdc3-469b-a208-e900f4570842",
                     "text": "Sadomba, Zvakanyorwa Wilbert",
                     "page": "pp. 245 - 248",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "cc162709-bdc3-469b-a208-e900f4570842",
                     "text": "Sadomba, Zvakanyorwa Wilbert",
                     "page": "pp. 245 - 248",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlidesGame\" style=\"margin-left:25%;\"><img id=\"img1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img1', '0%')\" src=\"images/Copan/Temple16Copan.png\" class=\"imgGameSize\"/><div style=\"position: absolute; bottom: 46%; left: 21.5%; font-weight: bold; font-size:1.4em\">ℕ</div><div style=\"position: absolute; bottom: 67%; left: 30%; font-weight: bold; font-size:1.4em;\">ℚ</div><div style=\"position: absolute; bottom: 67%; left: 10%; font-weight: bold; font-size:1.4em; border-width: 3px solid black; border-radius: 25px; color: black;background-color: #4CAF50;\">&nbsp&nbsp;π&nbsp&nbsp;</div><div style=\"position: absolute; bottom: 90%; left: 18%; font-weight: bold; font-size:1.4em;\">ℝ</div></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Figure 3</b>: Numerical groups positioned within the sacred mountains of Copán.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Cultural Exchange</b><br /><br />Mesoamerican constructions were made with superimpositions, which allowed us to fit the numbers into each level (<b>Figure 3</b>).<br /><br />From this, how would you adjust the numerical groups we studied within the space of the Shona kitchen?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
